# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: abbeville-county-south-carolina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The **1790 United States census** was the first United States census.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] It recorded the population of the whole United States as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article 1, Section 2, of the Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] In the first census, the population of the United States was enumerated to be 3,929,214 inhabitants.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Congress assigned responsibility for the 1790 census to the marshals of United States judicial districts under an act, which with minor modifications and extensions, governed census taking through the 1840 census.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Both Secretary of State Thomas Jefferson and President George Washington expressed skepticism over the results, believing that the true population had been undercounted.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] If indeed an undercount was the result, possible explanations for it include dispersed population, poor transportation links, limitations of contemporary technology, and individual refusal to participate.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Although the census was proved statistically factual, based on data collected, the records for several states (including Delaware, Georgia, New Jersey, and Virginia) were lost sometime between 1790 and 1830.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Almost one-third of the original census data have been lost or destroyed since their original documentation.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] At 17.8 percent, the 1790 census's proportion of slaves to the free population was the highest ever recorded by any census of the United States.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] 0 is the correct figure, and the 16 here should be added to the "All other free persons" column.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] When the census of 1790 was published in 1791, it reported 16 slaves, which were illegal in Vermont.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Subsequently, and up to 1860, the number is given as 17.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] An examination of the original manuscript by the Census Bureau superintendent found that there never were any slaves in Vermont.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The original error occurred in preparing the results for publication, when 16 persons, returned as "Free colored," were classified as "Slave" in Bennington County.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 85,425, or 114 less than figures published in 1790, due to an error of addition of several towns.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1790-united-states-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The **1800 United States census** was the second census conducted in the United States.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] It showed that 5,308,483 people were living in the United States, of whom 893,602 were slaves.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The 1800 census included the new District of Columbia.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The census for the following states were lost: Georgia, Kentucky, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] In comparison to the 1790 census, the 1800 census gathered additional information.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] The census was published in December 1801 and cost $66,109.04.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] This census is one of the several for which some of the original data are no longer available.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] Original census returns for Georgia, Kentucky, Mississippi, New Jersey, Tennessee, and Virginia were lost over the years.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1800-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1800 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] The **1810 United States census** was the third census conducted in the United States.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] It showed that 7,239,881 people were living in the United States, of whom 1,191,362 were slaves.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] The 1810 census included one new state: Ohio.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] The original census returns for the District of Columbia, Georgia, Mississippi, New Jersey, and Ohio were lost or destroyed over the years.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Most of Tennessee's original forms were also lost, other than Grainger and Rutherford counties.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] This was the last census with Virginia ranked as the most populous state.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Census taking was not yet an exact science.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and some drew up their own, resulting in pages without headings.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] Some enumerators did not tally their results.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] As a result, census records for many towns before 1830 are idiosyncratic.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] This is not to suggest that they are less reliable than subsequent censuses, but that they may require more work on the part of the researcher.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1810-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1810 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The **1820 United States census** was the fourth census conducted in the United States.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census included six new states: Louisiana, Indiana, Mississippi, Illinois, Alabama and Maine.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] There has been a district wide loss of 1820 census records for Arkansas Territory, Missouri Territory, and New Jersey.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The total population was determined to be 9,638,453, of which 1,538,022 were slaves.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The center of population was about 120 miles (193 km) west-northwest of Washington in Hardy County, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] This was the first census in which any states recorded a population of over one million—New York, Virginia, and Pennsylvania—as well as the first in which a city recorded a population of over 100,000—New York.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Also, in this census and the 14 subsequent ones, New York was the most populous state until being superseded by California in the 1970 census.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The 1820 census contains a great deal more information than previous censuses.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Several of these columns were for special counts, and not to be included in the aggregate total.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Doing so would have resulted in counting some individuals twice.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were asked to use double lines, red ink or some other method of distinguishing these columns so that double counting would not occur.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] For example, the count of free white males between 16 and 18 was a special count, because these individuals were also supposed to be tabulated in the column for free white males of age 16 and under 26.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] The other special counts were foreigners not naturalized, persons engaged in agriculture, persons engaged in commerce, and persons engaged in manufacture.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Census takers were also instructed to count each individual in only one of the occupational columns.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] For example, if an individual was engaged in agriculture, commerce, and manufacture, the census taker had to judge which one the individual was primarily engaged in.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1820-united-states-census] Before 1830, enumerators lacked pre-printed forms, and drew up their own, sometimes resulting in pages without headings, line tallies, or column totals.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] The **1830 United States census**, the fifth census undertaken in the United States, was conducted on June 1, 1830.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] The only loss of census records for 1830 involved some countywide losses in Massachusetts, Maryland, and Mississippi.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] It determined the population of the 24 states to be 12,866,020, of which 2,009,043 were slaves.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] The center of population was about 170 miles (274 km) west of Washington, D.C. in present-day Grant County, West Virginia.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a city—New York—recorded a population of over 200,000.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1830-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1830 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The **1840 United States census** was the sixth census of the United States.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Conducted by U.S. marshals on June 1, 1840, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 17,069,453 – an increase of 32.7 percent over the 12,866,020 persons enumerated during the 1830 census.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The total population included 2,487,355 slaves.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] In 1840, the center of population was about 260 miles (418 km) west of Washington, D.C., near Weston, Virginia (now in West Virginia).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] This was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals, as starting in 1850 a temporary office would be set up for each census under the purview of the Department of the Interior.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The 1840 census was the first that attempted to count Americans who were "insane" or "idiotic".
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Published results of the census indicated that alarming numbers of black persons living in non-slaveholding States were mentally ill, in striking contrast to the corresponding figures for slaveholding States.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Pro-slavery advocates trumpeted the results as evidence of the beneficial effects of slavery, and the probable consequences of emancipation.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] The memorial was submitted to the House of Representatives by John Quincy Adams, who contended that it demonstrated "a multitude of gross and important errors" in the published returns.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] In response to the House's request for an inquiry, Secretary of State John C.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] Calhoun reported that a careful examination of the statistics by the supervisor of the census had fully sustained their correctness.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] No microdata from the 1840 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1840-united-states-census] A compendium of data from the sixth census, organized by States, counties, and principal towns is available on the web site of the Census Bureau.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The **1850 United States census** was the seventh decennial United States Census Conducted by the Census Office, it determined the resident population of the United States to be 23,191,876—an increase of 35.9 percent over the 17,069,453 persons enumerated during the 1840 census.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total population included 3,204,313 enslaved people.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Although the official date of the census date was June 1, 1850, completed census forms indicate that the surveys continued to be made throughout the rest of the year.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census where there was an attempt to collect information about every member of every household and not only the head of the household.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Slaves were included by gender and estimated age on Slave Schedules, listed by the name of the owner.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Prior to 1850, census records had recorded only the name of the head of the household and broad statistical accounting of other household members (three children under age five, one woman between the age of 35 and 40, etc.).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was also the first census to ask about place of birth of free residents.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Hinton Rowan Helper made extensive use of the 1850 census results in his influential anti-slavery book *The Impending Crisis of the South* (1857).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This was the first census in which the US recorded a greater population than the United Kingdom (a year later) which it broke off from 65 years prior.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Full documentation for the 1850 population census, including census forms and enumerator instructions, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census collected a great amount of data that gave insight into the state of the U.S. economy in 1850.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Some of the data revealed the growth of the economy with regard to agricultural and manufactured production, international trade, federal debt, taxation, transportation, education, and land expansion.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculated the total land by state (in square miles), the total production of major goods and livestock per state (in respective units), the total value of each good produced, the total number of plantations per state, and various other statistics.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total agricultural production between in 1850 was calculated at about 1.3 billion dollars.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Total manufactured production was valued at just over one billion dollars.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This is a great increase over the totals estimated in 1820 and 1840.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Also, in total, the manufacturing industry recorded an overall profit of 43%.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census contains the total value of imports and exports by state, statistics and names of the major imports and exports, the total values of shipping by state, and the value of imports and exports with various individual countries.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The United States traded most with the United Kingdom.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The imports and exports with the United Kingdom were both valued around 145 million dollars.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census contains yearly federal debt totals, total federal revenues, and total expenditures from 1790 to 1853.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The total debt of the United States on July 1, 1854, was roughly 47.2 million dollars.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The census contains some calculation of total annual federal taxes, but it is incomplete.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It does however, give state taxation totals.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census calculates the total cost, size, and quantity of railroads and canals.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The funded debt for railroads and canals in 1853 was 130 million.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Their gross earnings were more than 38 million dollars.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census also contains estimates for growth in mileage of telegraphic lines in the United States.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] In 1853 the country contains 89 telegraph lines that stretched 23,261 miles (37,435 km).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] When published in 1854, the country had an estimated 30,000 miles (48,000 km) of telegraphic lines, a drastic increase.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census shows the great amount of territorial expansion that took place in the United States, following the Admission of Texas, the Oregon Treaty, and the Treaty with Mexico following the war in 1848.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] These three pieces of territory totaled an addition of more than a million square miles to the nation.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] In 1850, the United States contained 31 states and 4 organized territories (Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Utah).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 United States census can be seen as a historical document that gives insight into the state of the nation's economy in 1850.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] It is much more detailed and provides more information than the 1840 census.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This census was conducted during a very important period of growth and innovation in the United States, the Industrial Revolution.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The statistics in this census provide data on the rate of growth that was taking place in 1850, which resulted in the emergence of the United States as an economic world power.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Many of the statistics were compared to those of Great Britain and other world powers.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] This shows where the United States stood economically relative to the rest of the world.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Microdata from the 1850 population census are freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The Utah Territorial census was taken in 1851.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Secretary Broughton Harris refused to certify the census of Utah Territory.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Harris complained that Brigham Young had conducted the census without him, claimed several irregularities, and consequently withheld funds reserved for the census.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The controversy contributed to Harris' decision to join other Runaway Officials of 1851 and abandon his post in Utah Territory.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Relationships with the federal government continued to sour and eventually resulted in the Utah War.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] Local government officials feared having an enslaved population might impede the territory's quest for statehood, since certain members of Congress were concerned about expansion of slavery into the western territories.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] The 1850 census slave schedule for Utah Territory reported only 26 slaves, with a note that all of them were heading to California, and did not include any enslaved people remaining in the territory.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/1850-united-states-census] John David Smith estimates that there were 100 blacks in Utah by 1850, with two-thirds of them enslaved.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Both Abbeville County and the county seat, Abbeville, get their name from the town of Abbeville, France, the native home of an early settler.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The county was originally part of Ninety-Six District, South Carolina, but was designated Abbeville County in 1785, with parts of the county later going to the creation of the counties of Greenwood and McCormick.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County was settled by mostly Scotch Irish and French-Huguenot farmers in the mid-18th century.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The Treaty of Dewitt's Corner, a historic peace negotiation with the Cherokee Indians, was signed in Dewitt's Corner (which is now known as Due West) in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As a result of the treaty, the Cherokee tribe broke into two factions, one of which, the Chickamauga Cherokee, continued fighting area settlers for another 30 years.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County was a hotbed of secession before the Civil War and was also where the last Confederate council of war was held.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 1950 Abbeville County had a population of 22,456.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, this has grown to 24,295 people.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were nine documented lynchings in Abbeville, SC.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Nelson known as "James Macon","James Mason", 1894.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Anthony Crawford, a prominent landowner, farmer, businessman lynched for not selling his cotton at the price demanded.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County is in the Savannah River basin and the Saluda River basin.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Note: the US Census treats Hispanic/Latino as an ethnic category.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] This table excludes Latinos from the racial categories and assigns them to a separate category.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As of the 2020 census, the county had a population of 24,295, 9,818 households, and 6,248 families residing in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The median age was 45.0 years, with 20.3% of residents under the age of 18 and 22.6% of residents 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 94.2 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.7 males age 18 and over.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The 2020 PL data (see table) show the population remained predominantly White, with a large Black or African American minority and smaller American Indian and Alaska Native, Asian, Pacific Islander, and Hispanic or Latino communities.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Twenty-one percent of residents lived in urban areas and 79.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Of those households, 28.1% had children under the age of 18 living with them and 30.5% had a female householder with no spouse or partner present.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] About 28.7% of all households were made up of individuals, and 14.0% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 11,540 housing units, of which 14.9% were vacant.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Among occupied housing units, 77.2% were owner-occupied and 22.8% were renter-occupied, with the homeowner vacancy rate at 1.3% and the rental vacancy rate at 7.2%.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] At the 2010 census, there were 25,417 people, 9,990 households, and 6,939 families living in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The population density was 51.8 inhabitants per square mile (20.0/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 12,079 housing units at an average density of 24.6 units per square mile (9.5 units/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 69.6% white, 28.3% black or African American, 0.3% Asian, 0.2% American Indian, 0.4% from other races, and 1.1% from two or more races.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Those of Hispanic or Latino origin made up 1.0% of the population.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In terms of ancestry, 14.7% were American, 10.9% were Irish, 9.7% were English, 7.6% were German, and 5.6% were Scotch-Irish.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Of the 9,990 households, 31.5% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 49.2% were married couples living together, 15.3% had a female householder with no husband present, 30.5% were non-families, and 27.3% of all households were made up of individuals.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.45 and the average family size was 2.98.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the county was $33,143 and the median income for a family was $45,147.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $39,217 versus $29,199 for females.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $16,653.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] About 16.3% of families and 20.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 26.8% of those under age 18 and 16.2% of those age 65 or over.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] At the 2000 census, there were 26,167 people, 10,131 households, and 7,284 families living in the county.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The population density was 52 people per square mile (20 people/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 11,656 housing units at an average density of 23 units per square mile (8.9 units/km2).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The racial makeup of the county was 68.33% White, 30.29% Black or African American, 0.10% Native American, 0.23% Asian, 0.03% Pacific Islander, 0.31% from other races, and 0.71% from two or more races.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] 0.83% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] 22.1% were of American, 9.7% Irish, 6.7% English, 5.5% German and 5.3% Scotch-Irish ancestry according to Census 2000.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There were 10,131 households, out of which 31.70% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 52.20% were married couples living together, 15.30% had a female householder with no husband present, and 28.10% were non-families.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] 25.30% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.30% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The average household size was 2.51 and the average family size was 3.00.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In the county, the population was spread out, with 25.30% under the age of 18, 9.50% from 18 to 24, 26.70% from 25 to 44, 23.80% from 45 to 64, and 14.70% who were 65 years of age or older.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females there were 92.10 males.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 88.00 males.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The median income for a household in the county was $32,635, and the median income for a family was $38,847.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Males had a median income of $30,452 versus $21,045 for females.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The per capita income for the county was $15,370.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] About 10.10% of families and 13.70% of the population were below the poverty line, including 17.20% of those under age 18 and 16.90% of those age 65 or over.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Norris is the chairman of the Abbeville County Council, who also represents district 4.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 2013, long-time Abbeville County Sheriff Charles Goodwin pled guilty to misconduct in office.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] He was put on probation for five years, sentenced to 100 hours of community service, and ordered to pay $4,500 in restitution.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Abbeville County was a typical "Solid South" county in its voting patterns until 1948 when it voted for Dixiecrat candidate and South Carolina native Strom Thurmond against Democratic candidate Harry Truman regarding his support for Civil Rights, most importantly racial integration.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] It resumed voting Democratic until 1968 when a majority voted for American Independent Party candidate & southern segregationist George Wallace.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 1972 the county voted overwhelmingly for Richard Nixon, and since then Abbeville has showed strong endorsement towards the Republican Party.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] The last Democrat to carry Abbeville County was Bill Clinton in 1992 and 1996.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 1999, Abbeville County had the highest level of economic development and job creation per capita in all of South Carolina.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Throughout 2023 and early 2024, the unemployment rate of Abbeville has fluctuated around 4%.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In 2022, the GDP of Abbeville County was $666.9 million (roughly $27,450 per capita).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] In chained 2017 dollars, its per-capita real GDP was $22,685.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] According to the Bureau of Labor Statistics, Abbeville has 417 employment establishments (private and public organizations covered by unemployment insurance).
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] As of Q3 2023, some of the top 20 employers in the state include the city of Abbeville, Erskine College, Hardee's, Ingles, Prysmian Group, Sage Automotive Interiors, and Wayfair.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] There are two school districts in the county: Abbeville County School District takes up the majority of the area, while some parts are in the Greenwood School District 51.
[src:abbeville-county-south-carolina/abbeville-county-south-carolina] Most Abbeville County schools are part of the Abbeville County School District.
